{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 When the term is used in the context of human performance, }{\*\cs67\fs18\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-2 attention}
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2  refers to several characteristics associated with perceptual, cognitive, and motor \u173 ?activities that establish limits to our performance of motor skills. A common view of attention is that it relates to consciousness or awareness. When used in this way, attention refers to what we are thinking about (or not thinking about), or what we are aware of (or not aware of), when we perform activities. A related view extends the notion of attention to the amount of \u173 ?
