{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2  in }{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 the first part of}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2  this chapter as they relate to the types of situations described in the introduction.}
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }\pard\plain \s14\f0\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw1 For example, detecting performance-related in\u8209 ?\line formation in the environment as we perform a skill can be an attention-demanding activity. We observe and attend to the environment in which we move to detect features that help us determine what skill to perform and how to perform it. Although this observation and detection activity demands our attention, it does not always require that we are consciously aware of what we observe and detect that directs our actions.\par Since the earliest days of investigating human behavior, scholars have had a keen interest in the study of attention. For example, as early as 1859, Sir William Hamilton conducted studies in Britain \line }
{\fs18\expnd1\expndtw6 dealing with attention. Around the same time, \line }{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw1 William Wundt, generally acknowledged as the \ldblquote father of experimental psychology,\rdblquote  investigated the concept of attention at the University of Leipzig in Germany. In America, William James at Harvard University provided one of the earliest definitions of attention in 1890, describing it as the \ldblquote focalization, concentration, of consciousness.}
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw1 \rdblquote \par }\pard\plain \s15\f0\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa620\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\brdrb\brdrs\brdrw40\brsp276\brdrcf1\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18\expnd1\expndtw7 Unfortunately, this late-nineteenth- and early-}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-1\u173 ?twentieth-century emphasis on attention soon waned, as those under the influence of behaviorism deemed the study of attention no longer relevant to the understanding of human behavior. A renaissance in attention research occurred, however, when the practical requirements of World War II included the need to understand human performance in a variety of military skills. Researchers were interested in several \u173 ?
attention-related areas, such as the performance of more than one skill at the same time; the selection \line of, and attention to, relevant information from the performance environment; the performance of tasks where people had to make rapid decisions when there were several response choices; and the performance of tasks where people had to maintain \u173 ?
attention over long periods of time. The discussion in this chapter will address two of these issues: the \u173 ?simultaneous performance of multiple activities, and the detection of, and attention to, relevant information in the performance environment.\par }
