{\*\cs67\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 tion}{\fs20  compare human attention capacity to a single }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 source from which all activities must be funded. To illustrate this view, consider a rather simplistic analogy in which the available attentional resources exist within one large circle, like the one depicted in }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 figure 9.2. Next, consider as smaller circles the specific tasks that }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 require these resources, such as driving a car (task A)}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  and talking with a friend (task B). \line Each circle by \u173 ?itself fits inside the larger circle. But for a person to successfully perform both tasks simultaneously, both small circles must fit into the large circle. Problems arise when we try to fit into the large circle more circles than will fit.\par }
