{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5 \line }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5 capacity will increase or decrease according to his or her }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-5
arousal level.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5  }{\*\cs67\fs20\b\i0\expnd-1\expndtw-5 Arousal}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5  is the general state of excitability of a person, reflected in the activation levels of the person\rquote s emotional, mental, and physiological systems. If the person\rquote s arousal level is too low or too high, he or she has a smaller available attention capacity than he or she would if the arousal level were in an optimal range. This means that }
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-5 for a person to have available the maximum attention}{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-5 al}
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-5  resources, the person must be at an optimal arousal level.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-5 \par }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-6 Second, another critical factor determining whether }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-6 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
the amount of available attention capacity is sufficient for performing the multiple tasks is}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
the }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 attention demands, or requirements, of the tasks to be performed.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
 This factor is represented in Kahneman\rquote s model in figure 9.3}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  as the }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2
evaluation of demands on capacity.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  The important point here is that tasks differ in the amount of attention they demand. As a result, the person must evaluate these demands to determine if he or she can do them all simultaneously or if he or she will not be able to perform some of them.\par }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 Finally, }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3 three general rules influence how people allocate attentional resources.}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 One }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 rule}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3
 }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 is that we allocate attention to ensure that we can complete one activity. It is important to note here that }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 completing}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  one activity may not always be possible. Kahneman }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3
\line }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 indicated that an activity may not be performed }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4\u173 ?}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4
successfully if there is not enough capacity to meet the activity\rquote s demands or because the allocation of avail}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3
able attention was directed toward other activit}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 i}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 es.\par }{\fs20 A }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i
second rule}{\fs20  is that we allocate attentional resources according to our }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 enduring dispositions.}
{\fs20  These are the basic rules of \ldblquote involuntary\rdblquote  attention, which concern those things that seem to naturally attract our attention (i.e., distract us). We typically will \ldblquote involuntarily\rdblquote  direct our attention to (or be distracted by) at least }
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 two types of characteristics }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 \line }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0
of events}{\fs20  in our environment, even though we may be attending to something else at the time. An example of one of these types of characteristics is that the event is }
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 novel}{\fs20  for the situation in which it occurs. These events can be visual or auditory. In terms of novel visual events, think about why fans at a basketball game who sit behind the basket like to stand and wave objects in the air while a player is attempting to shoot free throws. Or, consider why you become distracted while driving your car when a ball rolls onto the street in front of you. That we spontaneously and involuntary \u173 ?
allocate our visual attention to novel events such as these is well supported by research evidence (see Cole, \line Gellatly, & Blurton, 2001; and Pashler }
{\fs20 & Harris, 2001, for excellent reviews of this evidence).\par }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 Unexpected noise}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
 also presents a novel event that spontaneously and involuntarily attracts our \u173 ?attention. For example, how many times have you directed your attention away from the person teaching your class to one of your classmates when he or she sneezes very loudly or drops a book on\u8239 ?
the floor? Consider a different type of example. Why is a professional golfer who is preparing to putt distracted by a spectator talking, when a basketball player who is preparing to shoot a free throw is not distracted by thousands of spectators yelling and screaming? The most likely reason is that the golfer does not expect to hear someone talking while preparing to putt, but for the basketball player, the noise is a common part of the game. As a result, the noise is novel in one situation but not in the other.\par }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 The second characteristic of events that will \u173 ?involuntarily direct our attention is the }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4
mea\u173 ?ningful\u173 ?ness}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  of the event to us personally. A classic example of this characteristic is known as the }
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4 cocktail party phenomenon,}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  which was first described in the 1950s (Cherry, 1953). Undoubtedly, you have experienced this phenomenon yourself. Suppose you are at a party in a room filled with people. You are attending to your conversation with another person. Suddenly you hear someone near you mention your name in a conversation that person is having with other people. What do you do? You probably redirect your \u173 ?
attention away from your own conversation to the person who said your name. Why did you do this? The reason relates to the meaningfulness of your name to you. Even though you were attending to your own conversation, this meaningful event caused you to spontaneously shift your attention. In sports, it is not uncommon to hear athletes say that while they are performing, the only person they hear saying something to them is the coach. Why? In this competitive situation, the person\rquote s coach is very meaningful to the athlete.\par }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 The }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4 third rule}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  governing}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4
 our allocation of attention relates to a person\rquote s }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4 momentary intentions.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4
 This phrase means that a person allocates attention in a situation according to his or her \u173 ?specific intentions. Sometimes, these intentions are self-directed, which means the person has personally decided to direct attention to a certain aspect of the situation. At other times, momentary intentions result from instructions given to the person about how or where to direct his or her attentional \u173 ?
resources. For example, if a physical therapist tells a patient to \ldblquote pay close attention to where you place your foot on the stair step,\rdblquote  the patient has the \ldblquote momentary intention}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 \rdblquote  to allocate his or her attention according to the therapist\rquote s instruction.\par }\pard\plain \s18\f6\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb260\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Multiple-Resource Theories}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s17\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs67\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 Multiple-resource theories}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  provide an alternative to theories proposing a central}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 -}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 resource pool of \u173 ?at\u173 ?tention resources. Multiple-resource theories contend that we have several attention mechanisms, each having limited resources. Each resource pool}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 is specific to a component of performing skills. Using a government analogy, the resources are available in various government agencies, and competition for the resources occurs only among those activities related to the specific agencies. The}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 most prevalent of the multiple-resource theories w}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 ere}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0
 proposed by Navon and Gopher (1979), Allport (1980), and Wickens (1980, 1992, 2008).}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \par }\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 Wickens proposed what has become the most popular of these theories. He stated that resources for processing information are available from three different sources. These are the }
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2 input and output modalities}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  (e.g., vision, limbs, and speech system), the }
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2 stages of information processing}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  (e.g., perception, memory encoding, response output), and the }
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw2 codes of processing information}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  (e.g., verbal codes, spatial codes). Our success in performing two or more tasks simultaneously \u173 ?
depends on whether those tasks demand our attention from a common resource or from different \u173 ?resources. When two tasks must be performed \u173 ?
simultaneously and share a common resource, they will be performed less well than when the two tasks compete for different resources.\par }
{\fs20 For example, the multiple-resource view would explain variations in the situation involving driving a car while talking with a passenger in the following way. When there is little traffic, driving does not demand many resources from any of the three \u173 ?
different sources. But when traffic gets heavy, \u173 ?resource demand increases from these two sources: input-output modalities and stages of information processing. These are the same two sources involved in providing attentional resources for carrying on a conversation with a friend. As a result, to maintain safe driving, the person must reduce the resource demand of the conversation activity.\par }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 An advantage of multiple-resource theories is their focus on the types of demands placed on various information-processing and response outcome structures, rather than on a nonspecific resource capacity. The resource-specific attention view provides }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \line }{\fs20 a practical guide to help us determine when task demands may be too great to be performed simultaneously. For example, if one task requires a hand response and one requires a vocal response, a person should have little difficulty performing them simultaneously, because they do not demand attention from the same resource structure. Conversely, people have difficulty performing two different hand responses simultaneously because they both demand resources from the same structure. }
{\fs20 (For a more in-depth discussion of the multiple-resource view see Hancock, Oron-Gilad, & Szalma, 2007.)\par }\pard\plain \s21\f6\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb374\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 the dual-task Procedure for Assessing Attention Demands\par }\pard\plain \s17\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 A common experimental procedure used to inves}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 tigate attention-limit issues is the }{\*\cs67\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw2
dual-task \line }{\*\cs67\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 procedure}{\fs20 .}{\fs20  The general purpose of experiments using }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
this technique is to determine the attention \u173 ?demands}{\fs20  and characteristics of the simultaneous perfor\u173 ?mance of two different tasks. Researchers typically determine the attention demands of one of the two tasks by noting the degree of interference caused on that task while it is performed simultan\u173 ?
eously with another task, called the }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i secondary task.}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 The }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 primary task}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1  in the dual-task procedure is typically the task of interest, whose performance experimenters are observing in order to assess its attention demands. Depending on the purpose of the experiment, the performer may or may not need to maintain consistent primary-task performance, when performing that task alone compared to performing it simultaneously with the \line secondary task.\par }
{\fs20 If instructions in the experiment require the participant to pay attention to the primary task so that it is performed as well alone as with the secondary task, then secondary-task performance is the basis researchers use to make inferences about the attention demands of the primary task. On the other hand, if the experiment does not direct the person to attend primarily to either task, performance on both tasks is compared to performance when each task is performed alone. You will see a variety of examples of the use of the dual-task procedure in this chapter and others in this book.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s21\f6\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb360\sa128\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 Focusing Attention\par }\pard\plain \s17\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 In addition to having to allocate attention among several activities, people also direct attention to specific features of the environment and to action preparation activities. This attention-directing pro\u173 ?
cess is known as }{\*\cs67\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 attentional focus}{\fs20 .}{\fs20  As opposed to attentional demands, which concern the allocation of attentional resources to various tasks that need to be performed simultaneously, attentional focus concerns the marshaling of available resources in order to direct them to specific aspects of our performance or performance environment.}
{\fs18 \par }\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 We can consider attentional focus in terms of both width and direction of focus. }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2
Width}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  indicates that our attention can have a }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 broad or narrow}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
 focus on environmental information and mental activities. }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 Direction}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
 indicates that our attentional focus can be }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 external or internal:}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  attention may be focused on cues in the environment or on internal thoughts, }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 plans, or problem-solving activities. Nideffer (1993)}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  showed that the broad and narrow fo\u173 ?
cus\u8239 ?widths }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 and the external and internal focus \u173 ?directions interact}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
 to establish four types of attention-focus situations that relate to performance.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
Individuals in performance situations require specific types of attentional focus to achieve successful performance. For example, a person needs a broad/external focus to walk successfully through a crowded hallway, but a narrow/external focus to catch a ball. Sometimes, situations require us to shift the type of attentional focus and the object of that attention. We do this by engaging in what is referred to as }
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 attention switching.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  It is an advantage to switch }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
attentional focus rapidly among environmental and situational pieces of information when we must use a variety of sources of \u173 ?
information for rapid decision making. For example, a football quarterback may look to decide if the primary receiver is open; if not, he must find an alternate receiver. In the meantime, the quarterback must make decisions \u173 ?
related to whether or not he is about to be tackled or kept from delivering a pass. Each of these activities requires attention and must be carried out in the course of a few seconds. To do this, the player must rapidly switch attention between external and internal sources of information.\par }
\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 However, certain kinds of attention switching can be a disadvantage in the performance of some activities. For example, a person performing a skill that requires a rapid, accurate series of movements, such as typing, piano playing, or dancing, will be more successful if he or she focuses attention on a primary source of information for extended periods of time. Problems can arise if the person\rquote s attention is switched too frequently between appropriate and inappropriate sources of information. For example, if a pianist is constantly switching visual attention from the written music to the hands and keys, he \u173 ?
or\u8239 ?she will have difficulty maintaining the precise timing structure required by the piece }{\fs20 \line }{\fs20 being played.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s18\f6\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb350\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Focusing Attention on Movements versus Movement Effects\par }\pard\plain \s17\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 If, as we just discussed, it is best for people to narrow their attentional focus while performing certain skills, a relevant question concerns the specific location of the attentional focus. Although Nideffer \line presented the direction options of internal and external to represent the location, there is an alternative way to use these terms when referring to the performance of a specific skill. Is it preferable to focus attention on one\rquote s own movements (}
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 internal focus}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 ) or on the effects of one\rquote s own movements (}{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2
external focus}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 )? This question has intrigued scientists for many years, which we can see if we look at the classic and influential work of William James (1890). He raised this same question more than a century ago and offered as an answer that the directing of attention to the \ldblquote remote effects\rdblquote  (i.e., outcome of a movement, or movement effects) would lead to better performance than attention to the }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \ldblquote close effects\rdblquote  (i.e., the movements). He presented an example of a reaching/aiming movement to illustrate his point: \ldblquote Keep your eye at the place aimed at, and your hand will fetch [the target]; think of your hand, and you will likely miss your aim\rdblquote  (p. 520).\par }
\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw3 The German scholar Wolfgang Prinz (1997) }{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw6 formalized this view by proposing the }{\*\cs67\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1
action effect hypothesis}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw4  (Prinz, 1997), which proposes }{\fs20 that actions are best planned and controlled by their intended effects. The theory basis for this hypothesis relates to how we code sensory and motor information in memory. Prinz contends that we represent both in memory in a common code, which argues against the separation of perception and action as unique and distinct events. Without going further into the theory issues involved, the }
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i common coding view}{\fs20  predicts that actions will be more effective when they are planned in terms of their intended outcomes rather than in terms of the movement patterns required by the skill.}
{\fs20  \par An interesting application of this hypothesis was reported in an article in }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i The New Yorker}{\fs20
 magazine (Acocella, 2003) about the great ballerina Suzanne Farrell. Although retired from performing, she teaches ballet to experienced students and \line professional dancers. In her teaching, she emphasizes that the dancers concentrate on the effect they want to create with movements rather than on the movements themselves. \par When researchers have \u173 ?
investigated the\u8239 ?action effect hypothesis, they have reported strong\u8239 ?support with evidence based on a variety of laboratory and sports skills }
{\fs20 and physical rehabilitation activities}{\fs20  (e.g., Wulf, 2013;}{\fs20  }{\fs20 Wulf & Lewthwaite, 2016; }{\fs20 Wulf & Prinz, 2001). One of the research methods for investigating this hypothesis has been to study the effects of attentional focus on motor skill performance and learning. The results of this research have been remarkably consistent in showing that when performers direct their attentional focus to the movement effects, they perform the skill at a higher level than when their attentional }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 focus is on their own movements. }{\fs20 It is important to note here }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 that research has shown that the focus of attention is also relevant for the learning of motor skills. We will discuss the influence of focus of attention on }
{\fs20 the learning of skills in more detail }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 in chapter 14 \line when we discuss verbal instructions and their \u173 ?
effects on skill learning.\par }\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 The reason an external focus of attention results in better skill performance has been the subject of some debate (see Wulf, 2013;}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  Wulf & Lewthwaite, 2016}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 ; and Wulf & Prinz, 2001, for a discussion of the various issues in this debate). However, the most commonly accepted reason is the }
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-4 constrained action hypothesis,}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3  which was proposed by Wulf and her colleagues (e.g., McNevin, Shea, \line & Wulf, 2003; Wulf, McNevin, & Shea, 2001). According to this hypothesis an internal focus \ldblquote constrains\rdblquote  the motor system because the performer consciously attempts to control it, which results in a disruption of the automatic motor control processes that should control performance of the skill. But when the performer engages in an external focus of attention, the automatic (i.e., nonconscious) processes control performance. Research support for this view has come from several studies that involved a variety of techniques, including dual-task probe reaction times and EMG assessment (see Wulf, 2013; Zachry, Wulf, Mercer, & Bezodis, 2005; and Gray, 2011, for brief reviews of these studies).\par }
{\fs20 It is important to note that other researchers have a slightly different explanation for why focusing externally leads to better performance. For example, Beilock and colleagues (e.g., Beilock, Bertenthal, McCoy, & Carr, 2004; Beilock, Carr, MacMahon, & Starkes, 2002) distinguish bet}
{\fs20\u173 ?}{\fs20 ween }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 skill-focused }{\fs20 attention, which is directed to }{\fs20 \line }
{\fs20 any aspect of the movement, and }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 environmental-focused }{\fs20 attention, which is directed away from the execution of the skill (and not necessarily on anything relevant to the skill itself). In contrast to Wulf and colleagues, Beilock argues that the appropriate focus of attention is determined by the performer\rquote s skill level. Because beginners tend to consciously control many of the details associated with performance, she believes that a skill-focused attention is appropriate early in learning. On the other hand, because highly skilled individuals have proceduralized most aspects of performance and execute skills automatically with little conscious attentional monitoring, she believes that an environmental focus of attention is better in the later stages of learning. \par }
{\fs20 Like Wulf and colleagues, Beilock proposes that skilled individuals suffer when they focus on controlling the skill because of interference with automatic control processes. Performance deteriorates because the skilled individual reverts to an earlier, less automatic form of movement control. The interference that results from consciously monitoring proceduralized aspects of performance has been referred to as the }
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i deautomatization-of-skills}{\fs20  hypothesis (Ford, Hodges, & Williams, 2005). It is also thought to be the basis for what is commonly referred to as }
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i choking}{\fs20  under pressure (Beilock, 2010; Beilock & Carr, 2001). Evidence to support the idea that novices perform better under skill-focused instructions and experts perform better when distracted from focusing on the skill itself has been provided for the skills of golf putting (Beilock et al., 2004) and soccer dribbling (Beilock et al., 2002; Ford et al., 2005). In summary, researchers agree that focusing attention on movements leads to poor performance of well-learned skills because attention to movement details interferes with automatic control processes. However, researchers disagree about whether beginners should focus their attention externally or on aspects of the movement.\par }
\pard\plain \s21\f6\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb300\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 Attention and Automaticity}{\fs21 \par }\pard\plain \s17\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 Automaticity is an important concept in our }{\fs20 understanding of attention and motor skill perfor\u8209 ?
\line mance. The term }{\*\cs67\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 automaticity}{\fs20  is commonly used to \line indicate that a person performs a skill or engages }
{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw6 in an information-processing activity with little or no }{\fs20 demands on attention capacity. We briefly considered the attention-capacity demands of a skill in }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 the discussion of the evaluation of the task demands }{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw6 component of Kahneman}{\fs20\expnd1\expndtw6
\rquote s model of attention. }{\fs20\u173 ?Some examples of these activities include (a) the visual search of the environment to assess the environmental context regulatory characteristics associated with performing a skill; (b) the use of }
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i tau}{\fs20  when moving toward an object to make or avoid contact with it, or when an object is moving toward a person who needs to catch or strike \u173 ?
it; (c) the storing of information in memory and the \u173 ?}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 retrieval of information from memory; (d) the selection}
{\fs20  of an }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 action to perform and the movement characteristics }{\fs20 that must be applied to carry out the action; and (e) the actual production of an action. From an }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2\u173 ?attention point of view, the question of interest here }{\fs20 concerns the demand, or need, for some amount of attention \u173 ?
capacity for each activity.\par }\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Kahneman\rquote s (2011) most recent views of automaticity are presented in his best-selling book, }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3
Thinking, Fast and Slow}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 . Although his book focuses }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 primarily on problem solving and decision making as they relate to cognitive operations, it also presents concepts relevant to many of the perceptual and motor issues discussed throughout our book. With respect to automaticity and attention, Kahneman }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 proposes two systems that operate differently but interactively, to help us solve problems, of which we have included performing a motor skill. }
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1 System 1}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 operates automatically and quickly with little or no effort or sense of voluntary control. For example, this }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 s}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 ystem operates when we detect that one object is more distant from us than another, or when we drive a car on an empty road. }
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1 System 2,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  on the other hand, allocates attention to the various activities that demand attention, such as preparing for the starter gun in a race, and maintaining a faster walking speed than is normal for a person. From this perspective, automaticity relates to attention as it allows us to perform certain activities without effortful mental activity, especially when we engage System 1. This system enables us to solve certain problems (mental, perceptual, and motor) by relying on intuition that has developed through learning, which typically results from experience and practice. But, some problems require more effort to solve; they require effortful mental activities }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 that }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 are also influenced by experience and practice.\par }\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 Logan (1985, 1988; Logan, Taylor, & Etherton, 1999), who has produced some of the most important research and thinking about the concept of automaticity and motor skill performance, views automaticity as an acquired skill that should be viewed as a continuum of varying degrees of automaticity. This means that rather than considering the attention-capacity demand of an }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 activity in terms of \ldblquote yes, it demands capacity,\rdblquote  or \ldblquote no, it doesn\rquote t demand capacity,\rdblquote  the continuum view considers automaticity as related to demanding varying amounts of attention capacity. Logan proposes that, as with skill, people acquire automaticity with practice. As a result, the degree of automaticity for a skill or information-processing activity may be only partially automatic when the attention demand of the activity is assessed.\par }
{\fs20 According to both Kahneman\rquote s and Logan\rquote s perspectives, a complex motor skill could involve activities that require a range of attention demands. For example, the movement component of passing a soccer ball may require no attention capacity because }
{\fs20 the kicking of the ball}{\fs20  can be performed automatically, but the preparation for making the pass (recall the discussion related to }
{\fs20 decision making in }{\fs20 action preparation in chapter 8) may demand full attention capacity.}{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 The neural components associated with automaticity as it relates to motor skill performance have also been investigated. For example, Poldrack and his associates (Poldrack et al., 2005) used fMRI procedures to show that different brain areas are active in the following situation. When performance of each of the two tasks in a dual-task situation [is] compared to when the secondary task does not interfere with performance of the primary task, which would indicate performance automaticity of the primary task. Their results indicated that the supplementary motor area (SMA) and putamen/globus pallidus regions are more involved with automaticity than when each of the two tasks demand attention, in which case the prefrontal regions are more active. }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 (For a more extensive discussion of the neural characteristics associated with }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
automaticity of motor skill performance see Lohse, }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \line }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 et al. 2014.)}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4
\par }\pard\plain \s21\f6\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb360\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 Visual Selective Attention}{\fs21 \par }\pard\plain \s17\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 In addition to the capacity limits of attention, the }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 selection of performance-related information in the environment is also important to the study of attention as it relates to the learning and performance}
{\fs20  of motor skills. This area of study is \u173 ?commonly referred to as }{\*\cs67\fs20\b\i0\expnd0\expndtw-1 selective attention}
{\fs20 . Of particular interest to researchers has been }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i visual selective attention,}{\fs20  which concerns the role of vision in motor skill performance in directing visual atten}
{\fs20\expnd2\expndtw8 tion to environmental information (sometimes }{\fs20 referred to as \ldblquote cues\rdblquote ) that influences the preparation and/or the performance of an action. Because the use of vision in this way is primarily an attention issue, it is included here rather than in chapter 7 \line where we discussed the roles vision plays in the control of several motor skills. }
{\fs20 (For a discussion of the neural basis of selective attention, see }{\fs20 Tyler }{\fs20 \line }{\fs20 et al., 2015 and}{\fs20
 Yantis, 2008.)\par }\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 Researchers have disputed since the end of the nineteenth century about whether visual selective attention is active or passive (sometimes phrased as \ldblquote top-down or bottom-up,\rdblquote  or \ldblquote goal directed or stimulus driven\rdblquote ). In terms of the information-\u173 ?
processing model in }{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 figure 9.1, the basis for this dispute concerns how we select information from the environmental context to process in the first stage. Do we visually select relevant environmental cues according to our action intentions and goals, or do we visually attend to environmental cues because of their distinctiveness or meaningfulness in the \u173 ?
situation? In their review of the visual attention research literature, Egeth and Yantis (1997) concluded that these two types of visual attention control \ldblquote almost invariably interact\rdblquote  (p. 270). This means that in most performance situations, our intentions and goals as well as certain characteristics in the environment influence our visual attention. In other words, although we may actively seek environmental cues based on our action intentions and goals, we may also attend to certain cues because of their distinct characteristics. You will see evidence of this active-passive visual attention throughout this discussion.\par }
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4 The term }{\*\cs67\fs20\b\i0\expnd-1\expndtw-4 visual search}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4  is used to describe the process of directing visual attention to locate relevant environmental cues. During the preparation process for performing many skills, people carry out visual search to select from the environment those cues that are relevant for the performance of a\u8239 ?
skill in a specific situation. In the following \u173 ?sections, we consider the actual process of selecting appropriate information from the environment, and give examples from various sport and everyday skills to illustrate how visual search is an important component of the performance of both open and closed motor skills.\par }
{\fs20 As you read the following sections, you may find it helpful to refer back to chapter 6, where we discussed various procedures researchers have used to investigate the role of vision in motor control. You will find that researchers who study visual selective attention have used these same procedures. }
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s18\f6\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb256\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Eye Movements and Visual Selective Attention\par }\pard\plain \s17\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 As you read in chapter 6, eye movement recordings track the location of central \u173 ?vision while people observe a scene. However, an important question arises concerning how well this procedure assesses visual selective attention. The rationale for the use of the procedure is that what a person is looking at (i.e., the point of gaze) should give researchers insight into what information in the environment the person is attending to. But there is an important research question here: Is this a valid assumption? Can we validly relate eye movements to visual attention?\par }
\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Two characteristics of the use of eye movement \line recordings provide an answer. First, research evidence has shown consistently that }
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 it is possible to give attention to a feature in the environment without moving the eyes to focus on that feature}
{\fs20  (see Henderson, 1996; Zelinsky et al., 1997; and Brisson & Jolicoeur, 2007, for \u173 ?reviews of this evidence). This would mean that \u173 ?
peripheral vision was the source of picking up the relevant information. However, it is }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 not}
{\fs20  possible to make an eye movement without a corresponding shift in attention. Second, because eye movement recordings are limited to the assessment of central vision, they do not assess peripheral vision. Research evidence has shown that peripheral vision is involved in visual attention in motor skill perfor\u173 ?
mance (see Bard, Fleury, & Goulet, 1994 for a brief review of this research). As a result of these two factors, }{\fs20 \line }{\fs20
eye movement recordings cannot provide a complete picture of the environmental features to which the person is directing visual attention. Therefore, eye movement recordings typically }
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 underestimate}{\fs20  what a person is visually attending to. However, even with these limitations, the recording of eye movements is a useful technique to provide reasonable estimates of those features in the environment that a person directs visual attention to as he or she prepares and performs a motor skill.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s18\f6\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb270\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 How We Select Visual Cues\par }\pard\plain \s17\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Theories concerning how we select certain cues in the environment address the selection of cues for nonmoving as well as moving objects. Both situations are important for the performance of motor skills. For example, visual search for regulatory conditions associated with stationary objects is critical for successful prehension actions. Without \u173 ?
detection of these conditions a person would not have the information needed to prepare and initiate movement to reach for and grasp a cup, or any stationary object.\par }
\pard\plain \s20\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb270\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs69\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Visual search and intended actions.}
{\fs20 \u8194\'20}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 The visual search for regulatory conditions in the performance environment is an active search that a person engages in according to the action he or she intends to perform. This means that the performer looks for specific cues in the performance environment that will enable him or her to achieve a specific action goal. For example, if a person intends to pick up a cup to drink from it, he or she will visually search for features of the cup and \u173 ?
en\u173 ?vironment that will indicate the movement characteristics to implement. This search could include looking to see how }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0
\line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 full the cup is, what type of liquid is in it, the location of the cup in terms of distance from the person, and whether or not there may be obstacles between the person and the cup. By actively looking for these features, the person can prepare the movement characteristics to reach for, pick up, and drink from the cup. This view of a visual search process fits well with the research evidence you saw in chapter 7 that showed the influence of various object and \u173 ?
environment features on prehension movement kinematics.\par }\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Research evidence also supports the view that we actively visually search the performance environment according to action intentions. For example, Bekkering and Neggers (2002) demonstrated that the focus of initial eye movements differed when participants in their experiment were told to point to or grasp an object. The intention to grasp an object directed participants\rquote  visual search to the spatial orientation of an object, whereas the intention to point to the object did not. The authors concluded that a specific action intention enhances the visual detection of those regulatory conditions that are relevant to the intended action.\par }
\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 It is also important to note that visual search does not always mean that a person performing a motor skill is actively seeking cues in the environment to respond to. On the contrary, there are times when a person detects cues as he or she performs \line a skill. These cues get attended to, but rather than having been actively searched for, they were detected by the performer as relevant to the situation, which then influenced the performer\rquote s movements accordingly.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s20\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs69\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 The feature integration theory.}
{\fs20 \u8194\'20}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 Although re}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0\u173 ?\u173 ?}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 searchers }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0
have proposed several theories to account for the characteristics of how we select \line certain cues in the environment and ignore others (see Neumann, 1996, for a review of these theories), one of the more popular theories is the }
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 feature integration theory}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  proposed by Treisman in the 1980s }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
(e.g., Treisman, 1988; Treisman & Gelade, 1980; see }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 also Chan & Hayward, 2009). This theory indicates that during visual search, we initially group stimuli together according to their unique features, such as color or shape. This grouping occurs automatically. These groups of features form }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \ldblquote maps\rdblquote  related to the various values of various features. For example, a color map would identify the various colors in the observed scene, whereas a shape map would indicate which shapes are observed. These maps become the basis for further search processes when the task demands that the person identify specific cues. For further processing, we must use attention, and must direct it to selecting specific features of interest. }
{\f4\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 The features of interest in an environmental context have a degree of }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2
salience}{\f4\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw0  to them, which means they have a specific amount of meaningfulness because of their presence in the situation. For example, the rotation characteristics of a pitched baseball are highly meaningful to a batter in a game situation. As a result the batter visually attends to the ball\rquote s rotation because of its salience as a visual cue about the type of pitch. (To learn more about the salience of visual cues in movement situations, read the Introduction in the article by Zehetleitner, Hegenloh, & M}
{\*\cs70\f9\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 \'9f}{\f4\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 ller, 2011.)}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \par }\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 The selection of features of interest occurs when a person focuses the }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw1
attentional spotlight}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1  on the master map of all features. People can direct attention over a wide or a narrow area, and it appears that the spotlight can be split to cover different map areas. If the person}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 \rquote s task is to search for a target having a certain distinct feature, then the target will \ldblquote pop out\rdblquote  as a result of this search process, because the feature is distinct among the groupings of \u173 ?
features. Thus, the more distinctive the feature is that identifies the target of the visual search, the more quickly the person can identify and locate the target. If the distinctive feature is a part of several cues, the search slows as the person assesses each cue in terms of how its characteristics match those of the target. (See }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 Wolfe, 2014 and }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 Hershler & Hochstein, 2005, for an extended discussion of feature integration theory and factors that influence the \ldblquote pop out\rdblquote  effect.)}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw1 \par }{\fs20 For movement situations, McLeod, Driver, Dienes, and Crisp (1991) proposed a }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0
movement filter}{\fs20  in the visual system that would allow visual \u173 ?at\u173 ?tention to be directed at just the moving items in the person\rquote s environment. They suggested that this movement filter mechanism can be related to \u173 ?
Treisman\rquote s feature integration theory}{\fs20 \rquote s emphasis }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 on the importance of grouping in visual search by }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 operating as a subsystem to a group\rquote s common movement characteristics. In light of this view it is interesting to note that Abernethy (1993) }
{\fs20 described research evidence to demonstrate that in sports \u173 ?involving fast ball action, such as racquet sports, skilled players visually search the playing environment for the }
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 minimal essential information}{\fs20  necessary to determine an action to perform. This information is an invariant perceptual feature of the performance context. We described one of these invariant features in chapter 7 when we discussed the importance of the use of time-to-contact information to catch a ball, contact or avoid an object while walking or running, and strike a moving ball.\par }
{\fs20 Abernethy indicated that another essential source of information to detect is the kinematics of an opponent}{\fs20 \rquote s action, which specify what he or she is going to do next. This information is contained in the grouping of joint displacements that define an opponent\rquote s pattern of coordination. As a person becomes more skillful, his or her visual attention becomes increasingly more attuned to detecting the important kinematic features, which provides the skilled player an advantage over the less-skilled player in anticipating the opponent\rquote s action in a situation. In effect then, this minimal essential information \ldblquote pops out\rdblquote  for the skilled player and directs the player\rquote s visual attention as he or she prepares an appropriate action to respond to his or her opponent\rquote s action.\par In addition to detecting essential information \line from an individual player, skilled athletes in dynamic team sports, such as basketall and soccer, \line visually select patterns of play, similar to what chess masters do while playing chess. For example, in a series of experiments by Williams, Hodges, North, and Barton (2006), skilled soccer players were quicker and more accurate than less-skilled players in recognizing familiar and unfamiliar game action sequences presented on film, as point-light displays, and with event and people occluded conditions on film.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s21\f6\fs21\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb360\sa120\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\keepn\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs21 Visual Search and Motor skill performance\par }\pard\plain \s17\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 Visual search picks up critical cues that influence three parts of the action control process: }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2
action \u173 ?selection, constraining of the selected action}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 (i.e., determining the specific movement features for performing the action), and }
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd-1\expndtw-3 timing of action initiation.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  By influencing these processes, the visual system enables a person to prepare, initiate, and execute the movements of an action that conform to the specific requirements of the performance context.\par }
\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Research investigating visual search in perfor\u173 ?mance situations has produced evidence about what }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
is involved in these important preparation and performance processes. }{\fs20 The following research ex\u8209 ?\line amples illustrate how \u173 ?
researchers have investigated a variety of sports and everyday skills, and provide a sense of what we \u173 ?currently know about the characteristics of visual search processes related to the performance of open and closed motor skills.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s18\f6\fs20\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs20 Visual Search in Open Motor Skills\par }\pard\plain \s20\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs69\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Returning a badminton serve.}
{\fs20 \u8194\'20}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 The experiments by Abernethy and Russell (1987) described earlier in chapter 6 provide the best example of \u173 ?
research investigations of visual search by expert badminton players. They found that the time \u173 ?between the initiation of the badminton server\rquote s backswing and the shuttle\rquote s hitting the floor in the receiver\rquote s court is approximately 400 msec (0.4\u8239 ?
sec). Within that time period, there appears to be a critical time window for visually picking up critical cues \u173 ?predicting where the shuttle will land. This window, which lasts from about 83 msec before until 83 msec after racquet-shuttle contact, provides information about racquet movement and shuttle flight that seems to resolve uncertainty about where the served shuttle will land. Experts use the 83 msec period prior to \u173 ?
racquet-shuttle contact more effectively than novices. As a result, experts have more time to prepare their \u173 ?returns. The racquet and the arm are the \u173 ?
primary sources to visually search for the anticipatory cues needed to prepare the return. }{\f4\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 In a series of experiments that extended the Abernethy and }
{\f4\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 \line }{\f4\fs20\b0\i0\expnd0\expndtw0 Russell study, Abernethy, Zawi, and Jackson (2008) found similar time-based characteristics }
{\f4\fs20\b0\i0 distinguishing}{\f4\fs20\b0\i0  expert from nonexpert badminton players. In addition, they found that the expert players visually focused on different kinematic information of their opponents than the nonexperts.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \par }\pard\plain \s20\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs69\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Returning a tennis serve.}{\fs20
\u8194\'20Results from two experiments by Goulet, Bard, and Fleury (1989) demonstrate how critical visual search strategies are to preparing to return tennis serves. Expert and novice tennis players watched a film showing a person serving and were asked to identify the type of serve as quickly as possible. The authors recorded the participants\rquote  eye movements as they watched the film. Three phases of the serve were of particular interest: the \ldblquote ritual phase\rdblquote  (the 3.5 sec preceding the initiation of the serve); the \ldblquote preparatory phase}
{\fs20 \rdblquote  (the time between the elevation of the arm for the ball toss and the ball\rquote s reaching the top of the toss); and the \ldblquote execution phase\rdblquote  (from the ball toss to \u173 ?
racquet-ball contact).\par }\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 As illustrated in figure 9.4}{\fs20 , during the ritual phase, the expert players focused mainly on the head and the shoulder/trunk complex, where general body position cues could be found. During the preparatory phase, they directed visual search primarily around the racquet and ball, where it remained until ball contact. An interesting note was that the experts also looked at the server\rquote s feet and knees during the preparatory phase. The important difference between experts and novices was that the visual search patterns of the expert players allowed them to correctly identify the serve sooner than novices could.\par }
\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 More recent research has supported the results of the Goulet et al. (1989) study in which the ball and the server\rquote s arm and racquet are the visual focus of attention for skilled tennis players preparing to return a serve. For example, Jackson and Morgan (2007) used an event occlusion procedure similar to the one described in chapter 6. Their results showed that when skilled tennis players could not see the server\rquote s arm and racquet or the ball prior to ball-racquet contact, their predictions of the ser\u8209 ?
\line vice court in which the ball would land were much worse than when they could see these components.\par }\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 In an effort to investigate the visual search characteristics of expert players in a more realistic setting, Singer et al. (1998) assessed the eye movement behaviors of five nationally ranked university male and female tennis players as they returned ten serves on a tennis court. Interestingly, all five players did not use the same visual search strategies. During the phases of the serve that Goulet et al. (1989) called the ritual and preparatory phases, the two highest-ranked players fixated primarily on the arm-racquet-shoulder region of the server, whereas two fixated on the racquet and expected ball toss area. All the players included head fixations during these phases. The players demonstrated more individual variation during the ball toss phase of the serve. Two players visually tracked the ball from the server\rquote s hand to the highest point of the toss, one player made a visual jump from the server}
{\fs20 \rquote s hand to the highest point of the toss, one player fixated only on the predicted highest point of the toss, and one player did not fixate on the ball toss but only on the racquet. Differences again were found for the visual search strategies used by the players after the server hit the ball. The two highest-ranked players visually tracked the ball to its landing location, two players did not track the ball after contact but visually jumped to the predicted landing location, and one player used a combination of these two strategies to return serves.\par }
\pard\plain \s20\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb240\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs69\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw2\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Baseball batting.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2
\u8194\'20}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 An example of research describing characteristics of the visual search processes involved in baseball batting is a study by Shank and Haywood (1987). They recorded eye movements for college and novice players as they watched a videotape of a right-handed pitcher as if they were right-handed batters. For each of twenty pitches, the players}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  indicated whether the pitch was a \u173 ?fastball or a curve. The expert players correctly identified almost every pitch, whereas the novices were correct only about 60 percent of the time. \u173 ?
Participants in both groups did not begin to track the ball until about 150 msec after the ball had left the pitcher\rquote s hand. During the windup, ex}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2\u173 ?\u173 ?}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 perts \u173 ?fixated on the release point, whereas novices \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2
tended to shift fixations from the release point to the pitcher\rquote s head.\par }\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 More recently, }{\fs20 Takeuchi and Inomata}{\fs20  (}{\fs20 2009}{\fs20 ) investigated the eye movements of expert baseball batters as they viewed the pitcher\rquote s motion during }
{\fs20 fastball}{\fs20  pitches. The distribution of eye movement fixations indicated}{\fs20 , in}{\fs20  results similar to those of Shank and Haywood, the batters}
{\fs20 \rquote  visual attention }{\fs20 was directed at}{\fs20  the }{\fs20 pitcher}{\fs20 \rquote }{\fs20 s}{\fs20  release point }
{\fs20 just prior to the pitcher}{\fs20 \rquote }{\fs20 s release of the ball}{\fs20 . \par }\pard\plain \s20\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb260\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs69\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd-1\expndtw-4\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Soccer actions.}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-4
\u8194\'20To determine whether to shoot, pass, or dribble in soccer, the player must use visual search that is different from that involved in the \u173 ?
situations described above. The soccer situation involves many players in the visual scene that must be searched for relevant cues. An experiment by Helsen and Pauwels (1990) provides a good demonstration of visual search patterns used by experienced and inexperienced male players to determine these actions. Participants acted as ball handlers as they viewed slides of typical attacking situations. For each, the person indicated as quickly as possible whether he would shoot at the goal, dribble around the goalkeeper or opponent, or pass to a teammate. The experts took less time to make the decision. Eye movement recordings showed that the experts gained this time advantage because they fixated on fewer features of the scene and spent less time at each fixation.\par }
\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Another visual search situation in soccer involves anticipating where a pass will go. Williams, Davids, Burwitz, and Williams (1994) showed that experienced players and inexperienced players look at different environmental features to make this \u173 ?
determination. Results based on subjects\rquote  eye-\u173 ?movement characteristics while watching an actual soccer game showed that the experienced players fixated more on the positions and movements of other players, in addition to the ball and the ball handler. In contrast, inexperienced players typically fixated only on the ball and the ball handler.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  More recently, Roca, Ford, McRobert, }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 and}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  Williams (2013) showed that skilled and less skilled soccer players employ different visual search strategies when the ball is in the offensive (far) versus defensive (near) half of the field.\par }
\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 Finally, Williams and Davids (1998) reported a comprehensive investigation of visual }{\fs20 selective}{\fs20  attention and search strategies of experienced and less-experienced soccer players in three-on-three and one-on-one situations. Among the many results in this study, two are especially noteworthy. One is that in the one-on-one situations, the experienced players visually fixated longer on the opponent\rquote s hip region more than the less-experienced players, which indicated their knowledge of the relevant \u173 ?
information to be acquired from the specific environmental feature. The other is that in the three-on-three situations, the experienced players used peripheral vision to select relevant information more than the less-experienced players. Evidence for the use of peripheral vision came from the \u173 ?
results of the spatial occlusion procedure, in which the masking of areas of the video scene surrounding the ball and the player with the ball had a more negative effect on the performance of the experienced players.\par }
\pard\plain \s20\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb260\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs69\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw2\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Shooting a basketball.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2
\u8194\'20When a basketball player shoots a jump shot, when does the player visually search for and detect the relevant information needed to determine when and how to make the shot? To address this question, }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 some}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  researchers }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 have}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  used the temporal occlusion procedure to investigate expert basketball players shooting a jump shot (}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 See, for example,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  Oudejans, van de Langenberg, & Hunter, 2002). The researchers established a simulated game situation in which the players watched a scene on a video projected in front of them. The players performed jump shots at a basket on the basis of the actions of the defensive players in the video. The players saw all, none, or only parts of the video. The results \u173 ?
indicated that the players\rquote  shooting performance was less successful when they could not observe the scene just \u173 ?before they released the ball. The \u173 ?
researchers \u173 ?concluded that to successfully shoot a jump shot, players determine their final shooting movement characteristics by visually searching for and using information detected until they release the ball. In agreement with and extending this conclusion, de Oliveira, Oudejans, and Beek (2008) showed that visual information was continuously being detected and used until the ball release, which demonstrated a closed-loop basis for control of shooting the ball.\par }
\pard\plain \s20\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb200\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs69\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd0\expndtw-2\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Driving a car.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
\u8194\'20Driving a car is a nonsport perfor\u173 ?mance situation in which vision provides information to select and constrain action. In a study that was done many years ago, but continues to be preferred as a demonstration of this role for vision, Mourant and Rockwell (1972) had novice and \u173 ?
experienced drivers drive a 2.1 mile neighborhood route and \u173 ?a 4.3 mile freeway route. The novices were students in \u173 ?
a\u8239 ?driver education class. The results of the eye movement recordings showed that novice drivers concentrated their eye fixations in a small area more immediately in front of the car. More \u173 ?
experienced drivers visually searched a wider area that was farther from the front of the car. This broader scanning range increases the probability for the \u173 ?
detection \line of important cues in the environment. On the freeway, the novices made pursuit eye\u8239 ?movements, whereas the experienced drivers made specific eye fixations that jumped from location to location. That is, the experienced drivers knew which cues were important and specifically searched for those cues. The experienced drivers looked into the rear- and side-view mirrors more frequently than the novices, whereas the novices looked at the speedometer more than the experienced drivers did.\par }
\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 In an extension of these findings}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 , Chapman and Underwood (1998) monitored eye movements of novice and experienced drivers as they watched various driving-related scenes that included at least one dangerous situation. In these situations, both types of drivers narrowed their visual search and increased the durations of their eye movement fixations. But the more experienced drivers tended to fixate for shorter amounts of time on specific parts of the scene than the novice drivers. This result indicates that more experienced drivers require less time to detect and process the information obtained from a fixation, which gives them an advantage in determining the appropriate driving action to take in the situation. In addition, the experienced drivers tended to be less variable in where they fixated their eye movements while watching the driving scenes, which, in agreement with the findings of Mourant and Rockwell (1972), indicates their greater knowledge of which environmental cues to look at to \u173 ?
obtain the most relevant information. The results of these two studies have been replicated in several other studies (see Falkmer & Gregerson, 2005}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 ,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  for a review of this research).}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 The relationship between attentional resources allocation and eye movements was demonstrated in research by Mackenzie and Harris (2017). Drivers who more successfully attended to relevant driving environment areas showed more effective eye movements related to scanning the roadway and relevant driving related tasks, such as looking at the vehicle}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \rquote }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 s mirrors and speedometer. These results add to those already discussed that establish the important role visual selective attention plays in driving safety.}
