{\*\cs69\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd-1\expndtw-3\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Prehension while walking.}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \u8194\'20When a person must walk to a table to pick up an object, such as a pen or book, visual search plays an important role in setting into motion the appropriate action coordination. An experiment by Cockrell, Carnahan, and McFayden (1995) demonstrated this role for visual search. Participants were required to walk 3.75 m to a table and pick up an aluminum can or a pencil as they walked by. Results showed that before they \u173 ?
began any prehensive action, their eyes moved to fixate on the \u173 ?target. Head movement also preceded the initiation of reaching movements. Thus, the eyes\rquote  searching of the environment to determine the location and characteristics of the object started a chain of events to allow the participants to grasp the object successfully.}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \par }\pard\plain \s20\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb220\sa0\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs69\f7\fs20\caps0\scaps0\b\i\ul0\strike0\expnd-1\expndtw-3\cf1\up0\nosupersub\charscalex100\outl0 Locomoting through a cluttered environment.}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \u8194\'20}{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \line Walking and running through a cluttered environment can occur in everyday situations\'d1we walk around furniture in the house or walk through a crowded mall\'d1and in sport situations: a player runs with a football or dribbles a basketball during a game. People}
{\fs20\expnd-1\expndtw-3 \rquote s ability to maneuver through environments like these indicates that they have detected relevant cues and used them in advance to avoid collisions. Visual search is an important part of this process.\par }
\pard\plain \s19\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 According to research by Cutting, Vishton, and Braren (1995), the most important cues involved in avoiding collision in these situations come from the relative location or motion of objects around the object the person needs to avoid. When visually fixating on the object he or she needs to avoid, the person uses relative-displacement and/or velocity information about both the object to be avoided and other objects in front of or behind the object. It is important to note that this decision making is done automatically by the visual system and provides the basis for appropriate action by the motor control system. The key practical point here is that the person needs to visually fixate on the object or objects that he or she wishes to avoid. (See }
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 Basili et al., 2013}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 , for a more extensive discussion of this point and related research; and Elder, Grossberg, & Mingolla, 2009, for a proposed neural model to explain how we avoid objects during locomotion.)\par }
