the ball than did the \ldblquote near experts\rdblquote  (they had made an average of 42 percent of their free throws during the just-completed season). This was especially the}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  case for the final eye movement }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 fixation just prior to the release of the ball which Vickers referred to as the \ldblquote quiet eye.\rdblquote  Second, as can be seen in \u173 ?
figure 9.5, the amount of }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 \line }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 time devoted to the \u173 ?final fixation prior to releasing the}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0  }{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 ball was related to the shooting success of the experts. They fixated on the backboard or hoop for just over 1.4 sec for shots they made, but almost 0.2 sec less for shots they missed. It is interesting to note that the final fixation duration for the near experts was just the opposite, with a longer fixation time on shots they missed than on shots they made. Vickers interpreted this finding as evidence that the near experts did not fixate long enough just prior to the release of the ball for the shots they made or missed to \u173 ?
allow them to attain the shooting percentage of \u173 ?the expert}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 s}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0 .}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw0
