{\fs18 Summary\par }\pard\plain \s23\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang2057
{\fs20 We have considered the concept of attention as it relates to human motor skill performance in two ways: the simultaneous performance of multiple activities, and the visual selection of performance-relevant information from the environment.\par }
\pard\plain \s24\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi240\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang2057
{\fs20 In the discussion of attention and the simultaneous performance of multiple activities, we discussed the following:}{\fs20
\par }\pard\plain \s25\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb120\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 People have a limited availability of mental resources, which was described as a }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2
limited attention capacity}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  for performing more than one activity at the same time.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1
\par }\pard\plain \s25\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb100\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i Kahneman\rquote s attention theory}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2  is an example of a centrally located, flexible limited capacity view of attention. His theory proposes that our attention capacity is a single pool of mental resources that influences the cognitive effort that can be allocated to activities to be performed. The amount of available resources (i.e., attention capacity) can increase or \u173 ?
decrease according to the general arousal level of the performer. The allocation of resources is influenced by \u173 ?several factors related to the person and the \u173 ?
activities.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw2 \par }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 Multiple-resource theories}{\fs20  provide an alternative view of a limited capacity view of attention by proposing that several different resource pools exist from which attention can be allocated. The resources are specific to a component of performing a skill. Wickens\rquote  model describes these components.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s25\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb100\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 The most common experimental procedure used to investigate the attention demands of motor skill performance is called the }
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i dual-task procedure.}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 Attentional focus,}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2
 which refers to where a person directs his or her attention in a performance situation, can be considered in terms of its width (i.e., broad or narrow) and direction (i.e., internal or external) or in terms of whether attention is focused on the movements or the movement effect.\par }
\pard\plain \s25\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb100\sa120\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 Automaticity}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-1  is an important attention-related concept that relates primarily to skill performance in which the performer can implement knowledge and procedures with little or no demand on attention capacity.\par }
\pard\plain \s23\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang2057
{\fs20 In the discussion of attention and the visual selection of performance-relevant information from the environment, we discussed the following:}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s25\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb120\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-2 Visual selective attention}{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2  to performance-\u173 ?relevant information in the environment is an important part of preparing to perform a motor skill.}
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 \par }{\fs20 The performer usually engages in an active }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw0 visual search}
{\fs20  of the performance environment according to the information needed to prepare and perform an intended action, although sometimes the environmental information attended to provides the basis for selecting an appropriate action.}
{\fs20 \par }{\fs20 The }{\*\cs65\fs20\b0\i feature integration theory}{\fs20  of visual selective attention is one of the more popular explanations of how people visually select and attend to certain cues in the performance environment and \u173 ?
ignore others.}{\fs20 \par }{\fs20 We looked at research related to the visual search involved in the performance of several different open and closed motor skills. Each skill provided evidence that effective visual search strategies are distinctly specific to the requirements of the action and to the skill level of the performer.\par Activity-specific training programs facilitate the use of effective visual search strategies more successfully than general-vision training programs.}
{\fs20 \par }\pard\plain \s26\f6\fs18\ltrpar\ql\fi0\li120\ri0\sb0\sa100\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf0\up0\charscalex100\caps\b\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar0\lang1033
{\fs18 Points for the Practitioner}{\fs18 \par }\pard\plain \s27\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb120\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20 The capability to do more than one activity simultaneously when performing a motor skill can be situation-specific. This means that a person may have more success in some situations than in others. Note these differences and use them as the basis for designing further instruction and practice.\par }
\pard\plain \s27\f4\fs20\ltrpar\qj\fi-170\li170\ri0\sb140\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl240\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs20\expnd0\expndtw-2 People will be more likely to be distracted while preparing to perform, or performing, a motor skill when events occur in the performance \u173 ?
environment that are not usually present in this environment.\par }{\fs20 Skilled individuals will be more likely to perform at their best when their arousal or anxiety levels are optimal for performing the skill in the situation they will experience.}
{\fs20 \par People will perform motor skills better when they focus their conscious attention (i.e., what they \ldblquote think about\rdblquote ) on the intended outcome of the movement rather than on their own movements.}
{\fs20 \par You can enhance a person\rquote s visual selective attention in performance situations by providing many opportunities to perform a skill in a variety of \u173 ?
situations in which the most relevant visual cues \u173 ?remain the same in each situation.\par Provide training for people to visually focus on the most relevant cue in the performance environment and then maintain visual contact with that cue just prior to initiating movement.}
