{\fs19 Attention and Cell Phone Use while Driving\par }\pard\plain \s37\f4\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-4 A common concern throughout the world is the use of cell phones by people who are driving motor vehicles. Many countries, and some cities and states in the United States, have passed laws that prohibit cell phone use while driving. In some instances, the laws prohibit the use of both handheld and hands-free cell phones, while in other cases, laws allow hands-free cell phone use. The following information, taken from an article by Strayer and Johnston (2001), provides some basis for concern.\par }
\pard\plain \s42\f4\fs18\ltrpar\ql\fi-155\li155\ri0\sb0\sa0\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-1 A study by the United States Department of \u173 ?Transportation indicated that as many as half of the motor vehicle accidents in the United States can be \u173 ?
related to driver inattention and other human error.}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-1 \par }{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-4 A survey of cell phone owners reported that approxi}
{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-3 mately 85 percent use their phones while driving, and 27 percent of those use the phones on half of their trips (Goodman et al., 1999; a summary of their }
{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-4 report is available online at http://www.nhtsa.dot.gov)}{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-4 .\par }{\fs18 A study of cell phone records of 699 people who had been involved in motor-vehicle accidents reported that 24 percent were using their cell phones within the 10 min period before the accident \u173 ?
(Redelmeier & Tibshirani, 1997).}{\fs18 \par }\pard\plain \s37\f4\fs18\ltrpar\qj\fi0\li0\ri0\sb0\sa0\tx240\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18 Although research evidence supports a relationship between cell phone use and motor vehicle accidents, the issue of cell phone use as the cause of accidents remains unsolved. However, researchers who have \u173 ?
investigated this issue, in either car simulators or \u173 ?simulated driving situations in laboratories, report \u173 ?evidence that indicates an attention-related basis for driving accidents. In their article, Strayer and Johnson reported a series of experiments in which participants engaged in a simulated driving task in a laboratory. The results indicated these things:\par }
\pard\plain \s42\f4\fs18\ltrpar\ql\fi-155\li155\ri0\sb0\sa0\facenter\sl220\slmult0\expnd0\expndtw0\cf1\up0\charscalex100\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\accnone\hyphpar1\lang1033
{\fs18 Participants missed two times more simulated traffic signals when they were engaged in cell phone conversations; and, when they responded correctly to the signals (i.e., red lights), their reaction time (RT) was significantly slower than when they were not using the cell phone.}
{\fs18 \par }{\fs18\expnd-1\expndtw-3 No significant differences were found between handheld and hands-free cell phone use for the number of missed traffic signals and RT (a result that is problematic for a multiple-resource theory of attention). (It is worth noting that a study by Treffner and \u173 ?
Barrett [2004] found critical problems with movement coordination characteristics when people were using a hands-free mobile phone while driving.)\par }
{\fs18 The generation of phone conversations influenced the number of missed traffic signals and RT more than did listening to the radio or to a section of a book on audiotape.\par }
