{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-1 Research by Joan Vickers and her colleagues discovered an important characteristic of visual search that is associated with successful motor skill performance. This characteristic, which they called the \ldblquote quiet eye,\rdblquote  occurs for both closed and open skills. The research evidence for the \ldblquote quiet eye\rdblquote  is based on the use of eye}
{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-1  }{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-1 movement recording technology, which was discussed in chapter 6. These recordings showed that when people search the performance environment, they typically fixate their gaze on a specific location or object for a certain amount of time (approximately 100 ms) }
{\*\cs65\fs18\b0\i\expnd0\expndtw-1 just before}{\fs18\expnd0\expndtw-1  initiating performance of the activity. This final gaze fixation is the \ldblquote quiet eye\rdblquote  (i.e., the \ldblquote quiet\rdblquote  portion of the visual search process). In terms of attention processes involved in motor skill performance, the \ldblquote quiet eye\rdblquote  characteristic of visual search demonstrates the importance of the visual focus of attention.*\par }
